\begin_layout Section*
Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the initial position as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{0}=6837432.552\hat{i}+1868795.099\hat{j}+1455480.629\hat{k}m
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and inital velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{0}=-2294.079\hat{i}+6758.849\hat{j}+2049.468\hat{k}m/sec.
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these data in the orbit.m code, the position and velocity of the satellite
 is calculated for 200 minutes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the results (subsequent pages ), the plot of the trajectory is elliptic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
minimum altitude = 852.503 km at
\series bold
 0.280533 h 
\series default
and 875.06 km at
\series bold
 1.12901 h
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total time elapsed in moving from minimum altitude to maximum altitude
 is half the time period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2*60*(1.12901-0.0280533)=101.8174$
\end_inset

 minutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The length of the major axis = sum of minimum and maximum altitude+earth
 diameter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2a=875.503+875.06+2*6378.137=14483.837km
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=7241.9185km
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ellipse centre to earth's centre measures 
\series bold
ae
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ae=7241.9185-6378.137-852.503
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which gives,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=0.0015574
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

