\begin_inset External
	template PDFPages
	filename prob 3 a.pdf
	extra LaTeX "pages=1-3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset External
	template PDFPages
	filename prob 3 b.pdf
	extra LaTeX "pages=1-3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the meteoroid is at 402000km with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=150^{0}$
\end_inset

and velocity v=2.23km/s, semi major axis can be computed from the specific
 energy relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\frac{\mu}{2a}=\frac{v^{2}}{2}-\frac{\mu}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2(\frac{v^{2}}{2}-\frac{\mu}{r})}}=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the previous problem, the total speed is obtained as the square of
 normal and radial velocities,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v^{2}=v_{r}^{2}+v_{\bot}^{2}=[\frac{\mu esin\theta}{h}]^{2}+[\frac{\mu(1+ecos\theta)}{h}]^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v^{2}=\frac{\mu^{2}}{h^{2}}[e^{2}sin^{2}\theta+1+e^{2}cos^{2}\theta+2ecos\theta]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v^{2}=\frac{\mu}{r(1+ecos\theta)}[e^{2}+1+2ecos\theta]
\]

\end_inset

This can be simplified to a quadratic in 
\series bold
e,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{2}+(2-\frac{v^{2}r}{\mu})cos\theta e+1-\frac{v^{2}r}{\mu}=0
\]

\end_inset

Since the meteoroid is known to be in a hyperbolic path, the positive root
 greater than 1 is taken as the eccentricity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=1.085983
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The radius at closest approach= 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{p}=a(e-1)=1.146873*10^{4}$
\end_inset

 km.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the alititude at closest approach = 11468.73-6378.14 km = 5090.59 km.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The velocity at closest approach can be computed from the energy relation,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\frac{\mu}{2a}=\frac{v_{p}^{2}}{2}-\frac{\mu}{r_{p}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{p}=\sqrt{2(\frac{\mu}{2a}+\frac{\mu}{r_{p}})}=6.021641km/s
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hyperbolic excess velocity is defined as the velocity when the body arrives
 at infinity.
 It can be computed from the specific energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\frac{v^{2}}{2}-\frac{\mu}{r}=\frac{v_{\infty}^{2}}{2}=\frac{\mu}{2a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{\infty}=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{a}}=1.72894km/s
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having known the semi major axis and eccentricity, the trajectory can be
 determined from the equation of hyperbola given by,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x^{2}}{a^{2}}-\frac{y^{2}}{a^{2}(1-e^{2})}=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As r
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+ecos\theta_{\infty})\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, therfore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta_{\infty}=cos^{-1}(\frac{-1}{e})=cos^{-1}(\frac{-1}{1.085983})=157.0469^{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset External
	template PDFPages
	filename problem 4.pdf
	extra LaTeX "pages=1-2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given mean anomaly 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{e}=$
\end_inset

and eccentricity 
\begin_inset Formula $e=$
\end_inset

, the eccentric anomaly can be obtained from the Kepler's equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{e}=E-esinE
\]

\end_inset

The difficulty in obtaining an analytical solution for E gives way to using
 Newton Raphson method to obtain 
\series bold
E.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=2.772571radians
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

